Tesla CEO Elon Musk reacts during the unveiling of the new Tesla Model Y in Hawthorne, California on March 14, 2019. AFP PHOTO | FREDERIC J. BROWN Billionaire Elon Musk has offered to buy Twitter for about $41 billion (Sh4.79 trillion), just days after rejecting a seat on the social media company's board. Musk's offer price of $54.20 per share (Sh6257.39), which was disclosed in a regulatory filing on Thursday, represents a 38 percent premium to Twitter's April 1 close, the last trading day before the TeslaÂ CEO's more than 9 percent stake in the company was made public. Twitter's shares jumped 12 percent in premarket trading. "Since making my investment I now realize the company will neither thrive nor serve this societal imperative in its current form. Twitter needs to be transformed as a private company," Musk said in a letter to Twitter Chairman Bret Taylor. "My offer is my best and final offer and if it is not accepted, I would need to reconsider my position as a shareholder," Musk said. Earlier this week, Musk said he had abandoned a plan to join Twitter's board, just as his tenure was about to start. Taking the board seat would have prevented him from a possible takeover of the company.